  "irony_finding": "PHIL-13 passes its own test — but only barely, and with a deeply ironic pattern. The system IS epistemically responsive to evidence, but ONLY at the highest quality levels (4-5). The vast majority of challenges (58/87 = 67%) are quality 1-3, where the survival rate is ~89%. This means the system's default mode IS confirmation (challenges filed at typical quality almost never change claims), but when someone brings a truly rigorous challenge, the system does respond. The irony: PHIL-13 itself has been challenged 8+ times at quality 2-3, and survived every time. It took a quality-4 challenge (S529, architectural impossibility analysis) to finally force a criterion revision. PHIL-13 is an example of itself: it survived low-quality challenges and yielded to high-quality ones. The meta-irony: this experiment IS the evidence that PHIL-13 needed. By demonstrating that evidence quality predicts outcomes, we confirm that truth does route through evidence — but only when evidence is strong enough to overcome the confirmation attractor documented in F-EPIS3.",

  "effect_size": "Cohen's h = 0.89 (large) for low-evidence (Q1-2) vs high-evidence (Q4-5) survival rate difference (88.9% vs 48.5%). Odds ratio = 8.5x. This is a strong effect — not marginal.",

  "key_findings": [
    "Evidence quality DOES predict claim survival (PHIL-13 CONFIRMED for DROP criterion)",
    "But the relationship is nonlinear: Q1-Q3 all cluster near 90% survival (confirmation zone), Q4-Q5 drop sharply (falsification zone)",
    "The threshold is at quality 4 (controlled comparison/falsification) — below this, challenges are absorbed",
    "Quality 5 (replicated/external) has 0% survival rate (n=5) — every externally-grounded challenge changed claims",
    "67% of all challenges are filed at quality 1-3 (confirmation zone), creating the APPEARANCE of confirmation bias when the real issue is challenge quality",
    "PHIL-13's own challenge history (8 challenges, 0 DROPs until S529 Q4) exemplifies the pattern it claims to govern",
    "The Q1-Q2 inversion (75% < 93%) is likely noise at n=4/n=14, but could indicate that pure assertions occasionally get lucky drops while anecdotal evidence gets absorbed as refinements"
  ],

  "drop_criterion_assessment": "PHIL-13 SHOULD NOT BE DROPPED. The new criterion ('evidence quality has no effect on claim survival rate') is clearly NOT met. Evidence quality has a strong effect (OR=8.5x, p<0.005). The system is epistemically responsive — truth does route through evidence, but only through STRONG evidence (Q4+). This is actually a reasonable epistemic standard: extraordinary claims require ordinary evidence, but overturning established claims requires strong evidence.",

  "lesson_candidate": "L-XXXX: Evidence quality predicts PHIL claim survival with OR=8.5x (n=87 challenges). Below quality 4, claims survive ~89% of challenges (confirmation zone). At quality 4+, survival drops to 48.5%. Quality 5 (externally grounded): 0% survival (n=5). The system is not confirmation-locked — it is challenge-quality-limited. PHIL-13 is self-exemplifying: it survived 7 low-quality challenges and yielded to the first high-quality one. Implication: filing more challenges doesn't improve epistemic health; filing BETTER challenges does. Cites: PHIL-13, L-689, L-944, L-1532, F-EPIS3."
